REST 

What is REST?

REST = Representational State Transfer

It is a rulebook for how web APIs should work. It uses HTTP methods (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE) and simple URLs.

How REST Works with Example

Pizza delivery app:

Action	        Method	    Example URL
See menu	    GET	        /menu
Place order	    POST	    /order
Update order	PUT	        /order/123
Cancel order	DELETE  	/order/123

Key Features of REST
1. Stateless (No Memory)
Every request is independent. Server does not remember past requests.
Benefit: Easy to scale. Any server can handle any request.

2. Resource Based
Everything is a "thing" with a URL.
Example: /users , /users/1

3. Uses HTTP Methods
Method	    Meaning
GET	        Read data
POST	    Create data
PUT	        Update data
DELETE	    Remove data

4. Returns JSON
Data comes in JSON format. Lightweight and easy for both humans and machines to read.

When to Use REST

Good for:

Public APIs like Twitter, GitHub
Web apps with React or Angular
Mobile apps

Avoid REST when:

You need very fast microservices (use gRPC instead)
You need real time communication (use WebSockets or gRPC)

REST in Kubernetes
Kubernetes itself runs on REST APIs.

Example:

GET /api/v1/pods → List all pods
POST /api/v1/namespaces/default/pods → Create a new pod

Even kubectl command line tool calls these REST APIs.

Real Benefit for IT Working
REST is simple and universal. Any programming language can use it. Browsers understand it easily. This makes REST perfect for public facing APIs where many different types of clients need to connect.

Final Summary
REST is the standard way to build web APIs
Uses HTTP methods (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE)
Stateless and returns JSON
Kubernetes itself uses REST internally
Use REST for public APIs and web apps
Use gRPC for fast internal microservices

